The URL you provided (http://localhost/stepwebsite/public/dynamic?name=Chandrika&phone=1234567890&message=Hai&btnsubmit=submit) seems to be a GET request URL with query parameters. It appears that you're passing form data as query parameters in the URL.

In the context of a typical form submission, this approach is not standard. Normally, when you submit a form using the POST method, the data is sent in the request body, not as query parameters in the URL.

To properly handle form submissions and check whether they are submitted correctly or not, you should follow these steps:

    HTML Form: Make sure you have an HTML form that specifies the method as POST. Include form fields such as name, phone, message, and btnsubmit.

    Server-side Script: Create a server-side script (PHP or another server-side language) to handle the form submission. This script will be responsible for processing the submitted data and taking appropriate actions (e.g., storing the data in a database, sending emails, etc.).

    Action URL: Set the action attribute of the HTML form to point to the server-side script that will handle the form submission.

    Submit Button: Ensure that the submit button's name attribute matches what your server-side script is expecting. In your case, it's btnsubmit.

    Server-side Handling: In the server-side script, you can access the submitted data using the $_POST superglobal in PHP. For example:

php

$name = $_POST['name'];
$phone = $_POST['phone'];
$message = $_POST['message'];

// Process the data (e.g., store in database, send emails)

// Return a response to indicate the form submission status
$response = array('status' => 'success', 'message' => 'Form submitted successfully');
echo json_encode($response);

    JavaScript Handling: In your JavaScript code, you can use the $.ajax function (or other similar functions) to submit the form data to the server-side script using the POST method. You can then check the response from the server to determine if the submission was successful.

Here's an example of how you might modify your JavaScript code:

javascript

$("#contactform").submit(function(e) {
    e.preventDefault();

    var formData = {
        name: $("#txtName").val(),
        phone: $("#txtPhone").val(),
        message: $("#txtMessage").val(),
        btnsubmit: "submit"
    };

    $.ajax({
        url: "path/to/server-side-script.php", // Change this to your server-side script URL
        type: "POST",
        dataType: "json",
        data: formData,
        success: function(response) {
            if (response.status === "success") {
                // Form submitted successfully
                console.log("Form submitted successfully");
            } else {
                console.log("Form submission failed");
            }
        },
        error: function() {
            console.log("An error occurred while submitting the form");
        }
    });
});

Remember to replace "path/to/server-side-script.php" with the actual path to your server-side script that handles form submissions. The server-side script should process the data and return a JSON response indicating the status of the form submission.

After submitting the form, check the browser console for the output messages to determine if the form was submitted successfully or if there were any errors. Additionally, you can check your server-side logs for any errors or confirmations related to the form submission process.
